<img width="777" height="437" src="../../../../wp-content/uploads/2017/01/textron-scorpion-777.jpg" class="attachment-content-single size-content-single wp-post-image" alt="Textron AirLand photo" srcset="../../../../wp-content/uploads/2017/01/textron-scorpion-777.jpg 777w,   ../../../../wp-content/uploads/2017/01/textron-scorpion-777-180x101.jpg 180w, ../../../../wp-content/uploads/2017/01/textron-scorpion-777-260x146.jpg 260w" sizes="(max-width: 777px) 100vw, 777px"/><span class="wp-caption-text">Textron AirLand photo</span>
</div>
		<div class="advertisement">
			<div class="sb-widget post-ad defen-widget"><div id="defen-5058044782fb8d3c60ed2d2731aba7d8"></div></div>		</div><p class="entry-meta">
<span class="entry-meta-author vcard author">Posted By: <a class="fn" href="../../../../author/oriana-pawlyk/">Oriana Pawlyk</a></span>
<span class="entry-meta-date updated">January 19, 2017</span>
</p>
	<div class="entry-content clearfix">
		<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">The </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Air Force</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"> intends to conduct an informal experiment of a potential light attack fighter aircraft the service could use in ongoing counterterrorism air campaigns, the serviceâs top general said Wednesday.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Chief of Staff Gen. David Goldfein said the Air Force is looking to programs such as Textronâs Scorpion to potentially provide an inexpensive fighter capable of performing close-air support missions.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">&#8220;Weâre right now just having this dialogue with industry partners,&#8221; Goldfein told reporters after speaking at an American Enterprise Institute event in Washington, D.C. &#8220;Making sure they know that weâre putting this on &#8212; dates, still to be determined. But probably around the springtime.&#8221;</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Goldfein, saying there is no request for information at this time, did not elaborate on how the experiment would be conducted or what it would entail &#8212; whether it would be just a viewing of various industry light attack aircraft, simulation trials or flight demonstration.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">His comments come days after Arizona Republican Sen. John McCain </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">released his white paper assessment</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"> on how the Defense Department should move forward in military spending.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">The former </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Navy</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"> pilot stressed that, while the service should sustain its </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">A-10 Thunderbolt II</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"> fighter fleet for close-air support, &#8220;the Air Force should procure 300 low-cost, light-attack fighters that would require minimal work to develop.&#8221;</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">&#8220;These aircraft could conduct counterterrorism operations, perform close-air support and otherÂ </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">missions in permissive environments, and help to season pilots to mitigate the Air Forceâs fighterÂ </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">pilot shortfall,&#8221; </span><a href="../../../../public/_cache/files/25bff0ec-481e-466a-843f-68ba5619e6d8/restoring-american-power-7.pdf"><span style="font-weight: 400;">McCain said</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;">. His comments echo those of officials such as Lt. Gen. James &#8220;Mike&#8221; Holmes, the serviceâs deputy chief of staff for strategic plans and requirements, who recently said the aircraft could help dilute the fighter pilot shortage and gradually increase readiness.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">McCain suggested the Air Force could procure &#8220;the first 200 of these aircraft by fiscal year 2022.&#8221;</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Goldfein said it is important to note, &#8220;This isnât a competition, itâs an experiment.&#8221;</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">&#8220;Weâre going to do this experiment and see whatâs out there, and Iâm expecting many of the companies to come forward,&#8221; he said.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Brig. Gen. Edward Thomas, director of Air Force public affairs, said Goldfein &#8212; who hasnât officially signed off on the experiment, dubbed OA-X &#8212; &#8220;believes it does make sense to look at opportunities to provide a â¦ cheaper, attack-type aircraft that can do the close-air support mission, that other countries, allies, can fly also. And do this in a way that doesnât require an </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">F-22</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"> or an </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">F-35</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"> over a permissive environment,&#8221; he said, mentioning Iraq and Afghanistan.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">With the current budget, &#8220;I donât believe there is anything specifically programmed for it right now,&#8221; Thomas said, noting the experiment is in its early stages and doesnât have any funding attached.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">The additional light attack aircraft &#8212; which would </span><a href="../../../../2016/10/28/air-force-flying-10s-indefinitely/"><span style="font-weight: 400;">not replace the serviceâs beloved A-10 Warthog</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> &#8212; &#8220;would relieve the pressure on other aircraft, maintenance crews, [and] it would give us some turning space with our other combat platforms,&#8221; Thomas said.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">In September, </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Holmes told Defense News</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"> that a less expensive aircraft could help the service alleviate the strain of maintaining its infrastructure, growing and training new pilot ranks, and adding more resources while simultaneously contributing to ongoing conflicts.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">&#8220;We donât think it would cost a lot of money, and itâs designed just to help us get our arms around [questions like], &#8216;What can you actually do? Does it actually contribute? Can it survive in different threat environments?â &#8221; Holmes said at the time. Â Â </span></p>
	</div>
</article>					<div class="advertisement">
